    {
      "id": "LKb6O6_HkaNhXJTWaEMfm",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 6.030852958904234,
      "y": 2606.7049647848617,
      "width": 851.7994384765625,
      "height": 150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1S",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1926823840,
      "version": 347,
      "versionNonce": 1491068832,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771515014270,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "I now have a high level design that satisfies my func req\nnext up, im going to go deep to satisfy my non func req\n\ndeep dive:\n- how does the location DB work? (need to have fast look up)\n- how does the ride matching ensure consistency to ensure no double matching of rides",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "I now have a high level design that satisfies my func req\nnext up, im going to go deep to satisfy my non func req\n\ndeep dive:\n- how does the location DB work? (need to have fast look up)\n- how does the ride matching ensure consistency to ensure no double matching of rides",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "-ZexipIacHAna7uC98Ebq",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -22.87294556010636,
      "y": 2940.028512911868,
      "width": 601.8795776367188,
      "height": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1T",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 949467040,
      "version": 303,
      "versionNonce": 321643104,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771515014270,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Pinging location service:\n6 Million drivers\n3 Million active users\n3 million / 5 secs = 600k transactions/sec(TPS) => high QPS",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Pinging location service:\n6 Million drivers\n3 Million active users\n3 million / 5 secs = 600k transactions/sec(TPS) => high QPS",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "csUs9PLzG3Ij3mEjIkTW_",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2475.889012154634,
      "y": 1973.2523503819666,
      "width": 512.0996704101562,
      "height": 225,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1U",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 478448224,
      "version": 362,
      "versionNonce": 1874981792,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771515014270,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "BAD SOLN\n1. XX Postgres XX\n- range query => determine driver within that lat, lng\n- B trees => optimized for 1-D data, not 2D\n    thus slow queries\nlarge # of rows to query\n- 2-4k transactions per sec\n    replicas etc.\n    => way off 600k",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "BAD SOLN\n1. XX Postgres XX\n- range query => determine driver within that lat, lng\n- B trees => optimized for 1-D data, not 2D\n    thus slow queries\nlarge # of rows to query\n- 2-4k transactions per sec\n    replicas etc.\n    => way off 600k",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "wS9lSRPbx6eHGH9feK2TJ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2473.5964731756,
      "y": 2235.5832562367696,
      "width": 899.8993530273438,
      "height": 400,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1V",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1928377952,
      "version": 730,
      "versionNonce": 1547736672,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771515014270,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "postgres\n- proximity searches via:\n    => Geospatial index\n- querying spatial data more efficient\n    PostGIS (quad trees)\npros: hierarchical structure is efficient for spatial data indexing, supporting fast retrieval\nwell suited for bounding box searches & spatial queries\nprecision is consistent across the map\n\ncons: more complex implementation than geo hash\n        with potentially higher computational overhead\n        requires more space for storage due to the structure & pointers\n        not as straightforward for location data as compared to single string representation\n        ** also that when new data come in, it needs to re-index itself\n\n(lowkey i might prefer to use geo hash)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "postgres\n- proximity searches via:\n    => Geospatial index\n- querying spatial data more efficient\n    PostGIS (quad trees)\npros: hierarchical structure is efficient for spatial data indexing, supporting fast retrieval\nwell suited for bounding box searches & spatial queries\nprecision is consistent across the map\n\ncons: more complex implementation than geo hash\n        with potentially higher computational overhead\n        requires more space for storage due to the structure & pointers\n        not as straightforward for location data as compared to single string representation\n        ** also that when new data come in, it needs to re-index itself\n\n(lowkey i might prefer to use geo hash)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "a3cW9dAi0gpDLD-2nsZQJ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -20.265462307892903,
      "y": 2901.082619051648,
      "width": 378.5797119140625,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1W",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1959007136,
      "version": 159,
      "versionNonce": 1988263840,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771515014270,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "deep dive 1: latency in matching service",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "deep dive 1: latency in matching service",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "cp-SEuBAyjY7S1rvhLVId",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -19.527787951004257,
      "y": 3069.1360459503544,
      "width": 1143.5592041015625,
      "height": 1300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1X",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1478602336,
      "version": 2500,
      "versionNonce": 144624224,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771515014270,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. HIGH QPS -> leading to geospatial indexing + in MEM redis cluster\n\n- generally using the rider's src dest, find the drivers in the current grid + all 8 directions\n\nusing geospatial index (proximity service)\n- lat lng in POSTgresql XX bad XX\n- quad tree on POSTgresql XX bad XX\n    => maybe add a Q to handle all the transactions coming in for loc updates\n    => batching them to write in batches (getting the 600k to 4k TPS)\n    => this still causes significant unnecessary latency,\n        loc DB will be mildly inaccurate since we need to\n        wait for all transactions to come in before writing to the DB\n- in MEM data store: redis\n    => handle 100k - 1 mil TPS\n    => redis supports geo hashing\n    => dont require maintenance of that additional hierarchical tree strcuture\n\nsplit the regions into 4s\nrecursively split the regions into 4s\nkeep splitting until the precision value we are happy with\n*prefixes are always the same within neighbouring grids UNLESS they are in far grids\n    => resolution is to always get curr grid + all 8 grids surrounding it\n    => relatively easy to calc\n    => easy to store (just string)\n    => no additional data structure\n*base32 encoding of this string\n\ngeohashing vs quad tree:\ngeo hashing\n- indiscriminate to density of the world\n- since world is split into evenly precise boxes\n- less good when there is uneven distribution of density of ocations\n- very good for high frequency of TPS\n- even though drivers density are quite different, becoz of high TPS, we prefer this\n\nquad tree\n- great for uneven distribution/ density of locations \n    dense new york city but no one in kansas\n- no high frequency on that udpates\n- denser areas - tree splits more, much smaller cells, many smaller leaves, more accurate\n- less dense areas - trees dont split much, large leaf region, few drivers\n    Each node stores:\n    - Bounding box (minX, maxX, minY, maxY)\n    - Number of drivers inside\n    => do not be mistaken, inside the leaf node, u still know driver info exact_lat, exact_lng, id\n\n2. dynamic update -> on client side (if not online OR in ride, etc.)\n- not online -> no need to update\n- in-ride => dont need to be picking up new drivers\n- speed => if they are parked, they dont need to be udpated that much since their location will not be changed mcuh\n- proximity => out in the boonies (far from demand)\n            => update less since they are less likely to be picked up",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. HIGH QPS -> leading to geospatial indexing + in MEM redis cluster\n\n- generally using the rider's src dest, find the drivers in the current grid + all 8 directions\n\nusing geospatial index (proximity service)\n- lat lng in POSTgresql XX bad XX\n- quad tree on POSTgresql XX bad XX\n    => maybe add a Q to handle all the transactions coming in for loc updates\n    => batching them to write in batches (getting the 600k to 4k TPS)\n    => this still causes significant unnecessary latency,\n        loc DB will be mildly inaccurate since we need to\n        wait for all transactions to come in before writing to the DB\n- in MEM data store: redis\n    => handle 100k - 1 mil TPS\n    => redis supports geo hashing\n    => dont require maintenance of that additional hierarchical tree strcuture\n\nsplit the regions into 4s\nrecursively split the regions into 4s\nkeep splitting until the precision value we are happy with\n*prefixes are always the same within neighbouring grids UNLESS they are in far grids\n    => resolution is to always get curr grid + all 8 grids surrounding it\n    => relatively easy to calc\n    => easy to store (just string)\n    => no additional data structure\n*base32 encoding of this string\n\ngeohashing vs quad tree:\ngeo hashing\n- indiscriminate to density of the world\n- since world is split into evenly precise boxes\n- less good when there is uneven distribution of density of ocations\n- very good for high frequency of TPS\n- even though drivers density are quite different, becoz of high TPS, we prefer this\n\nquad tree\n- great for uneven distribution/ density of locations \n    dense new york city but no one in kansas\n- no high frequency on that udpates\n- denser areas - tree splits more, much smaller cells, many smaller leaves, more accurate\n- less dense areas - trees dont split much, large leaf region, few drivers\n    Each node stores:\n    - Bounding box (minX, maxX, minY, maxY)\n    - Number of drivers inside\n    => do not be mistaken, inside the leaf node, u still know driver info exact_lat, exact_lng, id\n\n2. dynamic update -> on client side (if not online OR in ride, etc.)\n- not online -> no need to update\n- in-ride => dont need to be picking up new drivers\n- speed => if they are parked, they dont need to be udpated that much since their location will not be changed mcuh\n- proximity => out in the boonies (far from demand)\n            => update less since they are less likely to be picked up",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "dMkqhtH543oKbiZ4Z1PCh",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 5.479441221116417,
      "y": 2826.7564940945454,
      "width": 670.51953125,
      "height": 75,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
